text:
to conclude the series of #aweekofeypsloveniaswomen, we are embracing the last few categories were females stood up and out in the year 2018!

we are leaving all of you with the last few facts of how inspiring girls were in the last circular year!

today, we are putting out the statistics on media and chairs teams of our events in 2018: - 3 out of 5 editors were female,
- 45% of vice presidents were female,
- 47% of media team members were female,
- 57% of chairpersons were female!

we would like to thank all the ladies who have put their effort and hard work into our national committee in 2018!

we would like to end the series of #aweekofeypsloveniaswomen with the words we opened it with: "a new day is on the horizon, and when that new day finally dawns it will be because of a lot of magnificent women..." and we wish that more of eyp slovenia's members, as well as members of the eyp network would support the #metoo movement! let's #wetoo in 2019 together.

thank you.

text:
the womenâ€™s movement fought to bring hardships of womanhood to light; from suffrage rights to income inequalities, the movement has, and is, continually addressing issues that keep women from living a fully free life. 
however, a divide within the womenâ€™s movement, specifically between black and white women, has contributed to the rapid decline of the movement and hindered the effectiveness of a shared collective identity. according to black feminist scholar barbara smith, the black feminist movement focused on reproductive issues, equality in healthcare, the prevention of rape culture and sexual harassment, and other important issues. 
unlike the white feminists, black feminists are actively fighting against structural and institutional racism, as well. .
.
.
equality is for all ! 
if racial equality is not a topic of discussion - 
then there is no women's movement... .
no matter the race, sex, gender, beliefs 
united we stand for something 
divided we fall 4 anything. .
.
why not be a queen in 2019? why not be a black feminist? 
why not re-build trust between white women & black women? 
why not build a sisterhood that transcends the test of time....
.
. 
here's a toast to 2019 - another chance to get things right! 
here's to the year of strong women ...
.
.

text:
my 2018? i traveled to 12 countries (yes, one per month). it started with a breakup that propelled me to run away to rome for the weekend, where i got stranded and met up with another woman who also ran away to rome bc of some guy and we both spent the entire day traveling on 3 different trains to get to switzerland in order to fly back home without having to pay like a regular passenger does. but that's why we have to go through such convoluted steps in order to fly back home - we fly for free.

then i got stranded in portugal over the summer and had to pay $1000 in order to fly back home on time for work so i don't get fired, which in the end didn't matter anyway bc i got fired regardless in december not long after i reported a sexual harassment incident and i broke down crying at the vancouver airport, houston airport, newark airport, london heathrow airport about how evil they are to let a predator keep his job while i lose mine. #metoo is a sham.

but the odd part is i bumped into my ex half an hour after i was told i would be laid off and he is now back in my life (yes, he was the one who broke up with me and caused me to run away to rome in the first place). it came full circle in a way, 2018.

but good riddance! i surround myself with friends who are supportive of my nomadic lifestyle, of traveling and writing. i have the means to do so, and even more so now - i am supplied with an abundance of time starting in 2019. celebrating this day now with mimosa for breakfast (yes, just mimosa) and helping a friend move into her new temporary home. 
last night before the festivities, i went to dinner with friends at a chinese restaurant and we each got a fortune that matched what we were going through in our lives. this is what my fortune read.

2019 - i will stay at home. relax. write. plan a month or two by the italian riviera, the adriatic sea, and the rhine. and heal.

guppy new ear. happy nude leer. happy news steer. hubby new drear. puppy do mirror. bubbly mew dear. aptly new beer.

#ladyofleisure #crazyrichasian #2019 #unemployed #funemployed #newyear #newyearnewyou

text:
the womenâ€™s movement fought to bring hardships of womanhood to light; from suffrage rights to income inequalities, the movement has, and is, continually addressing issues that keep women from living a fully free life. 
however, a divide within the womenâ€™s movement, specifically between black and white women, has contributed to the rapid decline of the movement and hindered the effectiveness of a shared collective identity. according to black feminist scholar barbara smith, the black feminist movement focused on reproductive issues, equality in healthcare, the prevention of rape culture and sexual harassment, and other important issues. 
unlike the white feminists, black feminists are actively fighting against structural and institutional racism, as well. .
.
.
equality is for all ! 
if racial equality is not a topic of discussion - 
then there is no women's movement... .
no matter the race, sex, gender, beliefs 
united we stand for something 
divided we fall 4 anything. .
.
why not be a queen in 2019? why not be a black feminist? 
why not re-build trust between white women & black women? 
why not build a sisterhood that transcends the test of time....
.
. 
here's a toast to 2019 - another chance to get things right! 
here's to the year of strong women ...
.
.

.

.
.

text:
the womenâ€™s movement fought to bring hardships of womanhood to light; from suffrage rights to income inequalities, the movement has, and is, continually addressing issues that keep women from living a fully free life. 
however, a divide within the womenâ€™s movement, specifically between black and white women, has contributed to the rapid decline of the movement and hindered the effectiveness of a shared collective identity. according to black feminist scholar barbara smith, the black feminist movement focused on reproductive issues, equality in healthcare, the prevention of rape culture and sexual harassment, and other important issues. 
unlike the white feminists, black feminists are actively fighting against structural and institutional racism, as well. .
.
.
equality is for all ! 
if racial equality is not a topic of discussion - 
then there is no women's movement... .
no matter the race, sex, gender, beliefs 
united we stand for something 
divided we fall 4 anything. .
.
why not be a queen in 2019? why not be a black feminist? 
why not re-build trust between white women & black women? 
why not build a sisterhood that transcends the test of time....
.
. 
here's a toast to 2019 - another chance to get things right! 
here's to the year of strong women ...
.
.

text:
365 days.
52 weeks.
1 year.
you passed like a sigh.
in a hush you were gone.

i closed my eyes, it was jan '18.
i open my eyes wide, it's jan, '19.

a year of dreaming about lost dreams,
hoping for lost hope,
laughing about everything,
crying for attention,
dancing without fear,
fighting,
flying high,
broken hearts,
shattered souls,
minced trust,
a void of endless drama
a year of ups and downs

man in a wig divided a nation, built walls,
#metoo cringed us
earth warned us
wars fuelled us
money tumbled us
fools ruled us
drones burnt us
#terror scared us
floods drowned us
disaster shattered us
cow vigilante shamed us
mob lynching shocked us

yet we thrived

we flew beyond sky
sent a car ahead the precipice of time,
into the great beyond

labels didn't break us
enemies welcomed us
#refugees are with us
they're one of us
built homes
built hope

we thrived

we lost legends
said goodbyes to stars
welcomed babies with open arms
honoured artistes
welcomed gays, lesbians
united races

jumping on
swimming into a vortex of disaster
grabbing lifeboat of friends

thinking about that lost days
remembering lost legends

here's to 2019
a year of infinite possibilities
days of laughter
days of joy
days of wisdom
.
'however bad life may seem, when there is life, then there is hope'- sh.
.
.
.
.
.
.

name: Mohammed Rayaan
tweet_full:
365 days.
52 weeks.
1 year.
you passed like a sigh.
in a hush you were gone.

i closed my eyes, it was jan '18.
i open my eyes wide, it is jan, '19.

a year of dreaming about lost dreams,
hoping for lost hope,
laughing about everything,
crying for attention,
dancing without fear,
fighting,
flying high,
broken hearts,
shattered souls,
minced trust,
a void of endless drama
a year of ups and downs

man in a wig divided a nation, built walls,
#metoo cringed us
earth warned us
wars fuelled us
money tumbled us
fools ruled us
drones burnt us
#terror scared us
floods drowned us
disaster shattered us
cow vigilante shamed us
mob lynching shocked us

yet we thrived

we flew beyond sky
sent a car ahead the precipice of time,
into the great beyond

labels didn't break us
enemies welcomed us
#refugees are with us
they're one of us
built homes
built hope

we thrived

we lost legends
said goodbyes to stars
welcomed babies with open arms
honoured artistes
welcomed gays, lesbians
united races

jumping on
swimming into a vortex of disaster
grabbing lifeboat of friends

thinking about that lost days
remembering lost legends

here's to 2019
a year of infinite possibilities
days of laughter
days of joy
days of wisdom
.
'however bad life may seem, when there is life, then there is hope'- sh.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
ada e. yonath (born 22 june 1939) is an israeli crystallographer best known for her pioneering work on the structure of the ribosome.
she is the current director of the helen and milton a. kimmelman center for biomolecular structure and assembly of the weizmann institute of science.
in 2009, she received the nobel prize in chemistry along with venkatraman ramakrishnan and thomas a. steitz for her studies on the structure and function of the ribosome, becoming the first israeli woman to win the nobel prize out of ten israeli nobel laureates,  the first woman from the middle east to win a nobel prize in the sciences, and the first woman in 45 years to win the nobel prize for chemistry.

text:
hi friends! happy new year! we made it ğŸ˜Š

i wanted to start off the new year by reintroducing myself. my name is stevie. i am the founder of we are her, a nonprofit that helps survivors became healed, empowered, and restored through our online community.

her gives survivors a safe place to voice their story. over 50 survivors have shared their story on our blog (weareher.net). and many more have shared their story via instagram.

in october of 2016, i started her. myself and 4 other friends started sharing pieces of our story every week. then more friends contacted me and wanted to share. then all of a sudden, survivors i didnâ€™t know began to contact me. her kept growing and growing.

while my ultimate goal is to not need her anymore, i know thatâ€™s not attainable right now. too many survivors have come out of the woodwork to say #metoo.

so iâ€™m going into 2019 with a few more goals:
ğŸ”¹be more inclusive for male survivors. i had a male survivor tell me we post a lot of memes that bash males. i never want to make a survivor feel excluded. we have 1 male blog contributor out of 50 so i know her can do better here.
ğŸ”¹use more gender-neutral pronouns. not all of our survivors identify as female and i want to make sure weâ€™re doing a better job here.
ğŸ”¹including more survivors who are poc. this goal is very near and dear to my heart for several reasons. iâ€™m hispanic on my momâ€™s side of the family, and i know how underrepresented latinxs and other poc are when it comes to dv and sexual assault. many white women make leading headlines when women of color who endure the same thing never even make the news and itâ€™s not right. i also live in montana where women living on reservations here are severely underrepresented as well. itâ€™s time that changes in 2019 and herâ€™s going to do itâ€™s part in making sure that happens.
ğŸ”¹i want to do even more webinars and live events that you can all tune into.

so cheers to 2019! ğŸ¥‚ iâ€™m wishing all of you nothing but strength, peace, and an abundance of joy! sending you all my her love! -stevie ğŸ’™ğŸ’œ #weareher

text:
[the sun sets on 2018 on the gregorian calendar]
this was a year in which much of the unrest i have already went through was amplified and blown up and i was made to live it all over again. 
i felt i was was forced out of highlands university with a rapid combination of ableism and sexual discrimination/misogyny from the teachers and harrassment from a member of the community. in reality, i was liberated. these establishments do not hold safety or power for me.

i was able to identify the abusive patterns i had been through in my life and i tried to save others from that abuse. i learned much of my family and friends were conditional on them being able to abuse me and illicit my resources and have been learning about what it is like to make boundaries. i learned that the mainstream herbal medicine community is in a bad way right now, but i am so honored to have met members of the herbal community that care about herbal medicine, and they care about marginalized people and trauma survivors.

i learned that as a culture and even as a person, i wasn't centering the experience of marginalized people, and that i needed to do that to start building a better world. the thing i am the most thankful for in 2018 are womxn of color and indigenous womxn. i have learned so much from you, and i will continue to do so in the hopes that i can protect you better from the society that my ancestors have built, and that i benefit from, as my solemn duty.

i moved into an unfinished cottage with my love so that we may try to build a food forest farm together! our love has lasted the trial of this year even though it was our first year together and probably the hardest year of my life, we made it and we are looking forward to a magical farm year to share with you!

i have prioritized my self care, i'm building boundaries that no one (not even my family or lover) will disrespect. i got back into my art. i switched my scientific self study qeue into astrology/tarot/self care rituals/ancestral history and farm magic queue and i am building space for a music corner in my house to ensure i can continue to learn to express myself through the frequency of sound!

im evolving in a big way.ğŸ‘‡

i moved into an unfinished cottage with my love so that we may try to build a food forest farm together! our love has lasted the trial of this year even though it was our first year together and probably the hardest year of my life, we made it and we are looking forward to a magical farm year to share with you!

i have prioritized my self care, i am building boundaries that no one (not even my family or lover) will disrespect. i got back into my art. i switched my scientific self study qeue into astrology/tarot/self care rituals/ancestral history and farm magic queue and i am building space for a music corner in my house to ensure i can continue to learn to express myself through the frequency of sound!

lacking self defence 
in this world, no one will take care of anyone, except you yourself.
everyone should be able to protect themselves.
well, think of a person who is alone in an area surrounded by a group of individuals with cruel and narrow intentions, they can't call anyone because there is no time and they do not have any weapon. who will save them at that point?
the answer is, they themself , if they know the technique of self defense.
we all, as responsible citizens, should motivate everyone to learn self defense technique, because who knows maybe next time the victim is known to you.

repost @domzthompson: "you may not like this undercover video or the source of the original video.  however, itâ€™s important to understand what is happening in this video.  itâ€™s also important to understand what some of your tax dollars are being used for.  according to data released in recent years, the number of monkeys used for u.s. biomedical research hit an all-time high.  over 100,000 to be exact. use of animals in labs is very common not only here in the u.s., but worldwide.  itâ€™s important to note that nonhuman primates are not the only animals being used for research.  cats, dogs, rabbits, farmed animals and more are also used in private labs and universities around the world. the rise of testing of animals is because of the reported rise of diseases. itâ€™s also because of the demand for commercial and cosmetic product development. iâ€™m not going to deny some research in science has yielded some results some of us have benefited from however, this way of rd is outdated. there are now modern alternatives available and being proposed in ai technology and more, without the use or need for animals. some of these alternatives include the tissue-on-a-chip model, imaging, microdosing and more. the current traditional way of research and development using animals (it should be renamed to research and no development because no real solutions is happening in modern times) should be removed and replaced with alternatives in technology aforementioned. in summary, this is your tax money at work. i also think itâ€™s important for you all to be aware what is happening with these animals because i would want someone to inform me of the things i did not know of or contributed to.  but hey, maybe thatâ€™s just me because i do genuinely care about all animals. i hope you all do too. - dom âœŒğŸ½ğŸŒ±ğŸ˜

former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

selamat tahun baru teman-teman penyintas. .
kita telah berjalan sejauh ini. .
kita telah melewati malam-malam yang sangat berat itu. 
kita telah berhasil untuk terus hidup meski kita menginginkan sebaliknya.
hidup memang sangat berat tetapi mati juga menakutkan. 
kita punya tujuan ada disini.
kita akan terus berjuang. berperang. meninggalkan masa lalu itu dan bayangannya. 
menuju masa depan yang penuh harapan. 
sudah cukup semua penderitaan itu. cukup. 
saatnya kita mendapatkan kebahagiaan yang sesungguhnya bagian kita. 
saatnya kita mendapatkan kedamaian.

bagi admin tahun 2018 adalah lembar kesedihan dalam buku kehidupan mimin. titik nol. 
semoga tahun 2019 adalah lembar baru yang di isi dengan petualangan yang menyenangkan. 
selamat tahun baru teman-teman. 
tetaplah berjuang disana.

text:
new day, new dreams, new hopes..
.
.
definitely 2018 was a memorable year for us, #keralites . we started the year by tackling #nipah , one of the most deadliest virus in history. the whole world vowed before our #determination .
.
the next nightmare came in the form of #rain , which brought the worst #flood ever in 94 years of our state's history. from our sunken state, we rose up like a phoenix. the world saluted to our #brotherhood.
.
we smiled to the world with the blooming #neelakurinji , a once in a 12 years experience..
.
hashtags like #metoo , #sabarimala , #genderequality , #transgender have gone viral, ensuring #equality irrespective of the sex.
.
2018 was definitely a year to cherish as well as an year to learn some life lessons. let's hope 2019 goes all right.. have a happiest new year..
.
.
.
.
.
.
#happynewyear #travelphotography #travelholic #travelblogger #letsrebuildkerala #kerala
